 name <b>de Manville</b> (see   Mandeville   3).","Americanized form of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic) <b>Mansfeld</b>, a habitational name from a place so called in Saxony."]},{"name":"Manderville","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Mandeville  ."]},{"name":"Manwell","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Mandeville  ."]},{"name":"Manville","meanings":["English (Sussex and Lancashire): variant of   Mandeville  .","Altered form of   Mainville   1, a surname of Swiss French origin (see   Miville  ).","French: variant of <b>Menville</b>, a habitational name from Menville in Haute-Garonne, and also of   Mainville   2."]},{"name":"Mundell","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): variant of   Mandeville  .","Americanized form of German <b>Mündel</b> (or some other similar, like-sounding surname): nickname for someone with a prominent mouth, from Middle High German <i>munt</i>, <i>mündelīn</i> ‘(little) mouth’."]},{"name":"Monville","meanings":["Altered form of French   Mandeville  .","Walloon: habitational name from Monville in Namur province in Wallonia (Belgium), of the same etymology as in 3 below.","In some cases possibly also French: habitational name from Montville in Seine-Maritime or Monville in Calvados, both named with Old French <i>mont</i> ‘mountain, hill’ + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’."]},{"name":"Mandal","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Chandi, Sanjay, Sankar, Somnath, Aditi, Aditya, Ajit, Amala, Amitabha, Anil, Anirudh, Aparna.","Indian (northern states): from Sanskrit <i>maṇḍala</i>, a word that has several meanings, including ‘sphere’ and ‘halo’.","English (Cumbria; of Norman origin): variant of   Mandeville  ."]},{"name":"Montville","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Vernice.","Altered form of French   Mandeville  .","French: variant of   Monville  . This surname is very rare in France, found mainly in Creuse."]},{"name":"Manfull","meanings":["English (Midlands): probably a variant of   Mandeville  . Compare   Manville  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Maundeville was born about 1132, in Essex, England, United Kingdom, her father, Geoffrey de Maundeville, was 33 and her mother, Mrs Geoffrey de Maundeville, was 28. She married Henry Lambert in Essex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1132–":"umbes 1132–Surnud","1132–Female":"1132–Surnud","1128–1197":"1128–1197","1115–1154":"1115–1154","1154–1189":"1154–1189","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1105–1132":"1105–1132","1128":"1128","1105":"1105","1115":"1115","1189":"1189","Abt 1132":"umbes 1132","1100":"1100","1154":"1154","1132":"1132","1197":"1197","1130":"1130",", , Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom",", , , England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of, Essex, England":"Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Cravin, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1132–":"noin 1132–Kuollut","1132–Female":"1132–Kuollut","1128–1197":"1128–1197","1115–1154":"1115–1154","1154–1189":"1154–1189","1100–Male":"1100–Kuollut","1105–11